(145, 1, '2018-09-21 06:24:11', '2018-09-21 06:24:11', '<h3><strong>A Computer quality Speaker That Sounds, AND Looks Good!</strong>\nMay 1, 2013 review\nVerified Purchase</h3>\nI bought the Edifier Exclaim e10 quality speaker system for use with my laptop which has atrociously bad internal speakers. The Exclaims are a simple install, and made a world of difference. While not \"audiophile sound\" they are definitely fine sounding quality speakers.\n<h4><strong>The Good;</strong></h4>\nEye-catching, aesthetically pleasing design. Most speakers are rectangular boxes having all the good looks of a phone book. The Exclaims looks...cool...modern...in a sort of techno-punk way. Hey, anyone can build a good sounding, expensive, rectangular box that\'s ugly. But Edifier built a good sounding, and great looking speaker that won\'t make you cringe when you pay for it.\n\nSound is very good. Just don\'t turn them up WAY loud. If you do, distortion starts to raise its head. So, using your Exclaims to play your recording of the 1812 Overture (with the real cannon) full blast at your office Christmas party is out.\n\nTo get a better sounding, and louder playing speaker you\'d need to spend much, much more; like stepping up to $200 + more. Will those $200 speakers sound better than the $100 Exclaim? IMO, maybe (depending on which speakers you get) but twice as good? Hmmmm...I\'ve been an audiophile for many decades and in my experience probably not.\n\nBuild quality appears to be very good. They\'re made of plastic, and a little metal. But it\'s good quality plastic, and metal fit together with care. Not fancy, but nice and clever.\n<h4><strong>The Not-So-Good;</strong></h4>\nThe Exclaims stand tall, on a (relatively) narrow base. So, they\'re not as stable as the old rectangular box speakers. But we\'re not talking they-fall-over-every- time-a-cat-sneezes unstable. So, unless you\'re playing tennis at your desk, it\'s unlikely you\'ll knock the Exclaims over.\n\nThe woofer/passive drivers are exposed on the base; there are no screens to protect them from inquisitive fingers, pocking pens, stabbing pencils, rampaging quarterly report folders, a spilled latte-with-a-shot, or that porcupine your co-worker in the next prairie dog hole just threw at you.\n\nThe speakers input plugs into your computer headphone/speaker jack. So, when I moved my laptop I got a burst of static through the speakers, apparently caused by the speaker plug moving in the jack.\n\nBut these are three, very small nits to pick on an otherwise fine design. Am I happy with the speakers? Yes. Would I buy them again. Yes.\n\nA few people have commented that these speakers are anything but \"aesthetically pleasing.\" I\'ll run the risk of stating the obvious. Looks are highly subjective and so what is pleasing to one eye, may deeply offend another. I find the Edifiers pleasing to look at.\n\nHowever, my tastes tend to run to the eccentric. For example I find the early models of JVC stereo receivers good looking ....in an idiosyncratic industrial, boiler plate sort of way. Many others find those same receivers horrifying to look at. Bottom line is this: Take a close look at the photos of these speakers and decide for yourself before you buy if you like their looks. Beauty, as they say, resides in the eye of the person with the credit card.\n\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/dp/B009XGH2HG/ref=psdc_172471_t3_B00JVX5SI6#customerReviews\"><strong>Buy Here</strong></a>', 'Edifier Exclaim Bi-Amped Speaker System', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '90-autosave-v1', '', '', '2018-09-21 06:24:11', '2018-09-21 06:24:11', '', 90, 'http://musicreview/uncategorized/90-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
